  "text": "This review has focused on errors in quantification caused by tissue fraction and limited spatial resolution. However, other errors can also occur in making measurements of tumor uptake. One of the most important of these is caused by motion-either inadvertent motion by the patient or physiologic motion-for example, the motion caused by respiration or even the motion caused by cardiac contraction. These latter types of motion can often be thought of as producing ''blurring'' in the resultant image and so, from that point of view, yield PVE similar to those produced by an imperfect scanner resolution or reconstruction algorithm. Motion can also introduce large biases in tumor uptake estimates [CITATION_1] . The effort expended in attempting to correct partial-volume errors must therefore be balanced against the magnitude of the other errors that might also be present in the images.",
